            <section class="prose">
              <h2>What is the solidarity surcharge (Solidaritätszuschlag)?</h2>
              <p>
                The <strong>solidarity surcharge</strong> (German:
                <em>Solidaritätszuschlag</em>, often shortened to <em>Soli</em>)
                is an additional German tax levied on top of:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  personal <strong>income tax</strong> (Einkommensteuer), and
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>corporate income tax</strong> (Körperschaftsteuer).
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                It was introduced in 1991 to help finance the costs of German
                reunification and other federal projects. The statutory rate is
                <strong>5.5% of the income or corporate tax</strong>, but since
                2021 most individual taxpayers are fully or largely exempt.
              </p>

              <h2>How the calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This calculator follows the current structure of the German
                solidarity surcharge in a simplified way:
              </p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  It estimates your <strong>income tax</strong> (for
                  individuals) or <strong>corporate tax</strong> (for
                  companies).
                </li>
                <li>
                  It applies the
                  <strong>tax-free threshold (Freigrenze)</strong> and
                  <strong>phase-in zone</strong> for individuals.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It applies the <strong>full 5.5% rate</strong> for
                  corporations.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Core formula (full liability):</p>
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Solidarity surcharge} = 5.5\% \times \text{Income tax
                  or Corporate tax} \]
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-gray-600">
                  For individuals, the actual amount may be lower due to the
                  tax-free threshold and phase-in zone. The calculator
                  approximates these rules for recent years.
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>1. Individuals (employees, self-employed)</h3>
              <p>
                For individuals, the solidarity surcharge is based on your
                <strong>income tax liability</strong> after credits. Since the
                2021 reform:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Most low and middle incomes pay
                  <strong>no Soli at all</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  There is a <strong>phase-in zone</strong> where Soli gradually
                  increases.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Only high earners pay the <strong>full 5.5% rate</strong> on
                  their income tax.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                The exact thresholds are defined in German tax law and change
                over time. This tool uses typical values and approximations for
                recent years to give you a realistic estimate, but it is not a
                certified tax program.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Corporations</h3>
              <p>
                Corporations (e.g. GmbH, AG) generally still pay the
                <strong>full solidarity surcharge</strong> on their
                <strong>corporate income tax</strong>:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  \[ \text{Soli (corporation)} = 5.5\% \times
                  \text{Körperschaftsteuer} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator lets you enter your taxable profit and corporate
                tax rate (default 15%) and then applies the 5.5% surcharge.
              </p>

              <h2>Step-by-step example</h2>
              <h3>Example 1 – Individual employee</h3>
              <p>Assume:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Taxpayer type: Individual</li>
                <li>Filing status: Single</li>
                <li>Taxable income: €60,000</li>
              </ul>
              <p>The calculator will:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Estimate your income tax based on German tax bands (for
                  example, around €14,000–€15,000).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Check whether this tax amount is below the Soli
                  <em>Freigrenze</em> (tax-free threshold).
                </li>
                <li>
                  If it is below the threshold, your
                  <strong>solidarity surcharge is €0</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If it is in the phase-in zone, you pay a
                  <strong>reduced Soli</strong>.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Only above the upper threshold is the full 5.5% applied.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h3>Example 2 – Corporation</h3>
              <p>Assume:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Taxpayer type: Corporation</li>
                <li>Taxable profit: €250,000</li>
                <li>Corporate tax rate: 15%</li>
              </ul>
              <p>Then:</p>
              <ol>
                <li>Corporate tax = 15% × €250,000 = €37,500</li>
                <li>Solidarity surcharge = 5.5% × €37,500 = €2,062.50</li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Formulas used in the calculator</h2>
              <h3>1. Income tax estimation (simplified)</h3>
              <p>
                German income tax is calculated using progressive formulas
                defined in §32a EStG. For this calculator we use a simplified
                progressive model that closely approximates the official tax
                tables for recent years:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">
                  Simplified progressive structure:
                </p>
                <ul class="text-sm">
                  <li>
                    0% on income up to the basic allowance (Grundfreibetrag)
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    Progressively increasing rates on the middle income ranges
                  </li>
                  <li>Top marginal rate of about 42–45% on high incomes</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <p>
                This is sufficient for estimating the solidarity surcharge, but
                your actual tax may differ slightly due to deductions,
                allowances, and special rules.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Solidarity surcharge for individuals</h3>
              <p>
                In law, the solidarity surcharge for individuals is defined
                using a <strong>tax-free threshold</strong> and a
                <strong>phase-in formula</strong>. Conceptually:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>If income tax ≤ threshold: \[ \text{Soli} = 0 \]</p>
                <p>
                  If income tax is in phase-in zone: \[ \text{Soli} =
                  \text{reduced percentage} \times \text{Income tax} \]
                </p>
                <p>
                  Above the upper limit: \[ \text{Soli} = 5.5\% \times
                  \text{Income tax} \]
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                The calculator implements a smooth phase-in between the
                exemption threshold and the full rate to mimic the official
                rules.
              </p>

              <h2>Limitations and disclaimer</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  This tool is an <strong>educational estimator</strong>, not an
                  official tax calculator.
                </li>
                <li>
                  It does not handle all special cases (e.g. church tax
                  interactions, foreign income, complex deductions, investment
                  income with flat tax).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Tax law changes regularly; we aim to keep the logic up to date
                  but cannot guarantee accuracy.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p>
                For binding calculations, tax returns, or complex situations,
                always consult a qualified
                <strong>Steuerberater</strong> (German tax adviser) or your
                local tax office (<em>Finanzamt</em>).
              </p>

              <h2>FAQ about the German solidarity surcharge</h2>

              <h3>Is the solidarity surcharge still in force?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. The solidarity surcharge still exists in German tax law.
                However, since the 2021 reform, the vast majority of individual
                taxpayers no longer pay it, or pay only a small amount.
                Corporations generally continue to pay the full 5.5% on their
                corporate tax.
              </p>

              <h3>
                Does the solidarity surcharge apply to trade tax
                (Gewerbesteuer)?
              </h3>
              <p>
                No. The solidarity surcharge is levied on
                <strong>income tax</strong> and <strong>corporate tax</strong>,
                not on trade tax. However, trade tax itself can be substantial
                and is a separate municipal tax.
              </p>

              <h3>Is Soli included in my payslip?</h3>
              <p>
                If you are an employee and still liable for the solidarity
                surcharge, it will appear as a separate line on your monthly
                payslip and annual <em>Lohnsteuerbescheinigung</em>. If you are
                exempt, it will simply not be shown.
              </p>

              <h3>Can non-residents be subject to the solidarity surcharge?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes. If you have German-source income that is subject to German
                income tax or corporate tax (for example, rental income from a
                German property), the solidarity surcharge may also apply to
                that tax. The exact treatment depends on your residency status
                and any applicable double tax treaties.
              </p>
